<p><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> Cool! So the first is titled ‚ÄúPhoenix Rising.‚Äù Could you talk about what went into making this print?
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>SL:</strong> The phoenix one was the first print I ever did, and it was also the first time I‚Äôd done art in like, forever. I really wanted to do Asian imagery, and I think it was my first time incorporating Asian imagery into any artwork I was doing. One thing I wanted to do in that piece was [play with] the fenghuang (phoenix) and the dragon pairing. They are a really traditional heterosexual Chinese pairing, like yin and yang, or the emperor and the empress, man and wife. There‚Äôs some implication that the phoenix is pure and delicate and the dragon is strong and can attack, and in having two phoenixes as a pair instead I really wanted them to be interdependent, like, I didn‚Äôt want there to be a power dynamic. The way I portrayed them I wanted them to be both attacking an unseen opponent and both defending each other. I think that represents the kind of ‚ÄúFor Us, By Us‚Äù [attitude] I‚Äôd like to see in our community.
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> One of the members of Phoenix Rising was eventually invited to speak as part of the workshop. What did it mean to you to personally encounter these activists and artists who came before you?
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>SL:</strong> I got to meet two elders in person, one was Giselle Cohan, and she was one of the co-founders of Phoenix Rising, which was the first Asian American Lesbian newsletter in the United States, and it was basically a publication they‚Äôd send out monthly for several years. It had picnics, or like news about a gathering in the forest a bunch of Asian Queers did one weekend, and fundraisers and personals. It was super interesting because she works in tech [like me, and] the way she talks about herself she makes it seem like she has a pretty quiet life, despite [her involvement being] so seminal and so historical. [It] allowed me to unpack some of the guilt that I had about being here and being in tech and just the things that I was navigating. And then I also got meet Kitty Tsui, although we didn‚Äôt actually get to talk.
<br /><br /></p>

<div class="ImageComponent ImageComponent--medium" id="sen__kitty"><figure>
    <div class="ImageComponent--image-wrapper flex align-center">
      <img src="https://aliciawillett.s3.amazonaws.com/images/blog/sen-kitty.jpg" alt="A muscular woman with short hair is shown from the waist up, looking over her right shoulder at the viewer. Swirling, colorful cross-hatched lines describe her body, in contrast with a stark rectangular frame and black background" />
    </div> 
    <figcaption>Sen Ê£Æ. KITTY. Linocut on paper. 2019. Kitty Tsui (b. 1952, Hong Kong) is a Queer Bay-Area writer, bodybuilder, actor, artist and activist. A prolific writer whose works include WORDS OF A WOMAN WHO BREATHES FIRE, BREATHLESS ‚Äì EROTICA and SPARKS FLY, Tsui is also a leather woman and a prize-winning bodybuilder.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <script>
    preloadImage("sen__kitty");
  </script>
</div>

<p><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> Speaking of Kitty Tsui, you ended up honoring her with a print as well. It‚Äôs a really powerful image, with bold square lines framing the powerful contours and textures of Tsui‚Äôs athletic body ‚Äî a body that is literally busting out of the frame. 
<br /><br /></p>

<p>In your artist‚Äôs statement you reference Tsui in 1996, ‚ÄúGrowing up in Hong Kong, I heard all around me mothers yelling at their children: ‚ÄòSay nui, mo no, mo yung!‚Äô Dead girl, no brain, no use‚Ä¶ For me as an Asian/Pacific lesbian, silence is not an option. To ensure that we‚Ä¶be acknowledged as who we are. Women with a history‚Ä¶Women who survived being dead girls.‚Äù¬†(‚ÄúAsian Pacific Lesbian a.k.a Dead Girl, China Doll, Dragon Lady, or the Invisible Man‚Äù). 
<br /><br /></p>

<p>What do you think it means to be a ‚Äúdead girl‚Äù? I‚Äôve never heard that phrase before.
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>SL:</strong> I‚Äôd never actually heard it before either. I think the way Kitty was talking about it was probably talking about pretty misogynistic culture, and I think in that sense Chinese culture is very misogynistic.
<br /><br /></p>

<p>The other day my mom sent me this photo of an old Chinese scroll that had like two poems and I asked her to translate them for me and she said the first poem is about raising a daughter and how your daughter is the most delicate flower that you spend all your days watering and it grows so beautiful and slender and delicate and you do everything you can to make it grow as beautifully as possible, and one day a man comes and plucks it with no thanks to you! And then the second half is about raising a son, like raising a son is like opening a bank account that you deposit all your money into, and you work so hard and you deposit everything into it, and then one day this woman comes and just takes the whole bank account without any gratitude. And I‚Äôm like, ‚ÄòThis is like so awful, why would you send me this??‚Äô So I think there‚Äôs all this history of the one child policy and how there aren‚Äôt enough girls because everyone only wanted men, because they keep the family line going, etc. etc., and women aren‚Äôt necessarily supposed to be out there having their own opinions. It‚Äôs very confusing, I don‚Äôt really get it. But I think maybe that‚Äôs partially what it‚Äôs about‚Ä¶
<br /><br /></p>

<p>OH actually, I just found it: In this Cantonese dictionary, there‚Äôs this term ‚Äúbad girl,‚Äù like in the way you might say to you cat ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre being a bad girl!‚Äù It‚Äôs an abusive term for a bad girl, and the characters in it are literally like ‚Äúdead‚Äù ‚Äúdaughter‚Äù or ‚Äúdead‚Äù ‚Äúwoman‚Äù.
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> I mean I guess people say some mean things to their kids when they want them to behave. It‚Äôs funny how people say so many throw-away things to children when they‚Äôre young and we really internalize them and remember them even after we‚Äôre much older. The way Tsui holds up this memory as she‚Äôs encouraging other Queer Asians not to be silenced is a really cool piece of writing. First in the way she humanizes herself as not this invincible activist but a person who still grapples with her past to be able to speak her truth. It also reminds me of the slogan from the AIDS crisis ‚ÄúSilence = Death,‚Äù implying that together her community can turn it on its head. Like if silence will kill you, speaking your truth might make you more alive.
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>SL:</strong> I like that a lot. That reminds be a little bit of this Junot Diaz‚Äôs quote: 
<br /><br />
‚Äú‚Ä¶if you want to make a human being into a monster, deny them, at the cultural level, any reflection of themselves. And growing up, I felt like a monster in some ways. I didn‚Äôt see myself reflected at all. I was like, ‚ÄúYo, is something wrong with me? That the whole society seems to think that people like me don‚Äôt exist?‚Äù And part of what inspired me, was this deep desire that before I died, I would make a couple of mirrors. That I would make some mirrors so that kids like me might see themselves reflected back and might not feel so monstrous for it.‚Äù
<br /><br /></p>

<div class="ImageComponent ImageComponent--medium" id="sen__ping-chang-xin"><figure>
    <div class="ImageComponent--image-wrapper flex align-center">
