<p><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> How did it feel to share all of this with the world at the closing reception?
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>SL:</strong> It felt really good. It was such a trip. It was really packed, and it was really interesting to have people come up to me and say ‚ÄùWow, your art made me think about these things,‚Äù which was really sweet. Katie [Gilmartin, printmaker and creator of the Queer Ancestors Program] said one of her favorite parts about being the featured artist is you can talk to anyone you want at the entire event, and you‚Äôll always have an excuse to do so, and I loved that, it‚Äôs so true. And as somebody who likes being able to meet people and not having to deal with social pressures or cues it was great to be able to show up at this thing, dress however the fuck I want. It was my first time really being in ‚Äúthe art world‚Äù and knowing without the shadow of a doubt that I could take up as much space as I wanted, and that made a lot of sense in the room.
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> That‚Äôs so inspirational. I think there are definitely lessons in there that I‚Äôm trying to learn‚Ä¶ And it sounds like you ended up finding what you were looking for when you first engaged with the Queer Ancestors Project?
<br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>SL:</strong> Yeah, I think so! Maybe instead of feeling less like an impostor I feel I care less about the idea that there are rules or that there‚Äôs an institution I‚Äôm trying to break into.</p>

<p><br /><br /></p>

<p><strong>AN:</strong> I think you definitely have a lot to say. Thanks so much for talking with me and sharing this experience. I‚Äôm looking forward to see what you make next!
<br /><br /></p>

